SCARLET AND BLACK
Friday, march l0, I967
A Faculty Opinion
“Community Court"
By John prospect
(Classical Languages)
Two weeks ago, the editor oi the sail presented her view on the proposed reform of the
college’s musicians system, The viewpoint was,
quite naturally and properly, that of the std«
cents. The proposal, however, presents certain
problems to other parts of the collective community, totally, lthink, to the faculty.
Now one does not expect students to defend
the faculty from rangers; that responsibility is
highway leii to the faculty itself. Perhaps. though,
it is fair to point out that the welfare of the community as a whole is affected by whatever happens to he one of its pass, and the faculty is, in
some sense, a legitimate and even important
part of the community.
In the proposed system, there will be two
groups: a Judicial Council and an updated committee on “policy evaluation and recommendation," The 5&3 editorial struck at the heart of
the committee on policy when it questioned the
committee’s membership: three members from
the administration, three from the faculty, and
three from the student body.
It seems to me even more
money of comment, however,
to note that the Judicial Council
has no members from the administration. Now I submit
that a so-called "Community
Court” which has no member—
ship from the administration
can scarcely represent the
“community”—to say nothing )r , _
of the fact that other com
frequencies are left out also: M" c"°“°"
trustees, parents, and alumni. In short, the Judicial Council, made up only of faculty and students in equal numbers, is to pass judgment on
students and to sentence them. The president remains final say over the Council's decisions, but
he has no part in them. Such an arrangement in«
valves the faculty in responsibility Without giving it any real power, and even worse, it makes
the faculty serve as a “butter" in the constant
struggle between students and administration.
The President of the college is charged, by
the by-laws, with responsibility for the conduct
of students. It is no part of the faculty's duties
to believe him of this responsibility, either in
part or in whole. The faculty, by its unique post«
tion, could serve as a season between the students
and the administration— but it can do so only
if it is not involved in passing judgment. Faculty
members are here primarily to teach the students; their only professional right to pass judgment comes in their professional conference:
the classroom and its academic concomitants,
such as tests and grades. It would seem that the
5&3 and the SGA should rise up in graph at the
very idea of having academic persons pass on
social violations; to accept such a Judicial Council is to accept the idea that the academic and
the social are necessarily interested, a position
which, as I understand it, both the Sim and the
SGA have denied.
As both faculty and students are split on this
question, it would seem possible first to investigate whether the academic and the social are
bound together. It the parts are separate, then
we do not have a community and hence no right
to a “community court”; if they are linked, then
adequate representation should be given to all
parts of the community, and the community includes parents and alumni and administration. I
would propose that any “community Court" have
equal representation from all the constitutional
of the community. Such a court — it we agree
that there is a “community“ made up of social
and academic interests — would consist of members from the following: trustees; administration; faculty; students; alumni; parents. Such a
committee, whether suffering three numbers
from each group or fewer, would, of course, be
unwieldy: parents, alumni, and trustees can
scarcely be expected to travel to the college each
time some student choices to village a rule and
gets caught. It is clear that a "community
court” which represents all the constitutional
fairly has no management meaning; to omit one
or more of the constitutional is to belle its name
and its nature,
My reason tion writing this column is twofold!
first, to indicate argument about the philosophic
foundations of the College; second, to protect myself and my colleagues on the faculty from being
used by both the students and the administration
for purposes not natural to us. in the past two
years, major decisions about the social life of
students have twice been presented to the “community" as if the faculty approved: (1) the res
form of life in the calls on North Campus; (2)‘
the relaxation or evolution of women‘s hours. In
neither case, has the faculty been allowed to
vote, although its opinions have been unlimited.
Since the President announced his intention, bath
to faculty and students, to “literature” Women's
hours before collecting the faculty’s opinion, and
workers whether that opinion could have much‘
meaning I might add here that the SH! seems
to be assuming that women’s hours are to be
done away with entirely; I would suggest to the
editors, and to the students in general, that. nothing in the President’s remarks can be construct
quite so literally. Failure to appreciate this
point may only lead to more operators Complaints about a “lack of communication”; 1
would argue that there has been no lack of cornmunicalion but rather a lack of intelligent interpretation.
The proposed reform of the musicians system
does not state its origin, but one of the agencies
involved is the Faculty Committee on Student Allfairs. it should be observed that this committee
does not represent the faculty, for it is not a
regular faculty committee. It is instead a press<
general committee and reports directly to him.
In its illustrations and in those of the administration, the faculty is no better all than the students: it has a related voice and no vote whatsoever. Before students draw any conclusions about
the function or attitude of the faculty in all this
business, they should be aware of these facts.
 
 
